comments.body:
we've change the code and no tests were updated, which signals to me that our coverage is lacking: the CI won't complain when the current change is invalidated in any way.

We have an arith_uint256_tests already, we could add a simple test there that proves why we need this change (which fails before the change and passes after):
```patch
diff --git a/src/test/arith_uint256_tests.cpp b/src/test/arith_uint256_tests.cpp
--- a/src/test/arith_uint256_tests.cpp	(revision 77c120d6bf1c214b30992ee5723c063d6fb638f9)
+++ b/src/test/arith_uint256_tests.cpp	(date 1757362769804)
@@ -65,6 +65,8 @@
 
 BOOST_AUTO_TEST_CASE( basics ) // constructors, equality, inequality
 {
+    static_assert(std::is_trivially_copyable_v<arith_uint256>);
+
     BOOST_CHECK(1 == 0+1);
     // constructor arith_uint256(vector<char>):
     BOOST_CHECK(R1L.ToString() == ArrayToString(R1Array,32));
```

It would also prove that the original version would pass the tests:
```patch
diff --git a/src/arith_uint256.h b/src/arith_uint256.h
--- a/src/arith_uint256.h	(revision 3eea9fd39532eeda648e44de365fc4c9112f6fc6)
+++ b/src/arith_uint256.h	(date 1757363002301)
@@ -37,21 +37,6 @@
             pn[i] = 0;
     }
 
-    base_uint(const base_uint& b)
-    {
-        for (int i = 0; i < WIDTH; i++)
-            pn[i] = b.pn[i];
-    }
-
-    base_uint& operator=(const base_uint& b)
-    {
-        if (this != &b) {
-            for (int i = 0; i < WIDTH; i++)
-                pn[i] = b.pn[i];
-        }
-        return *this;
-    }
-
     base_uint(uint64_t b)
     {
         pn[0] = (unsigned int)b;
```
I don't mind the explicit one suggested in https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/pull/33332#discussion_r2329076580, but I personally don't see why it's better, as long as we have a test that already guarantees what we're after (note: the PR description still mentions the removal).

I don't insist on removing needless code since others seem to prefer it, but I do insist on adding test for this.

